label.value: exocytic insertion of neurotransmitter receptor to postsynaptic membrane

value.value: The exocytic fusion of neurotransmitter receptor containing vesicles with the postsynaptic membrane resulting in the integration of NT receptors, enabling them to participate in neurotransmitter reception. This process includes tethering and docking steps that prepare vesicles for fusion.

label.value: neurotransmitter receptor transport postsynaptic membrane to endosome

value.value: Vesicle-mediated transport of a neurotransmitter receptor complex from the postsynaptic membrane to the postsynaptic early endosome.

label.value: neurotransmitter receptor transport to postsynaptic membrane

value.value: The directed movement of neurotransmitter receptor to the postsynaptic membrane in transport vesicles.

label.value: postsynaptic neurotransmitter receptor diffusion trapping

value.value: The process by which diffusing neurotransmitter receptor becomes trapped at the postsynaptic specialization membrane. This is typically due to interaction with components of the post-synaptic specialization.

label.value: anterograde dendritic transport of neurotransmitter receptor complex

value.value: The directed movement of a neurotransmitter receptor complex along microtubules in nerve cell dendrites towards the postsynapse.

label.value: anterograde dendritic transport of mitochondrion

value.value: The directed movement of mitochondria along microtubules in dendrites towards the postsynapse and away from the cell body.

label.value: structural constituent of postsynaptic actin cytoskeleton

value.value: The action of a molecule that contributes to the structural integrity of a postsynaptic actin cytoskeleton.

label.value: postsynaptic actin cytoskeleton organization

value.value: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of cytoskeletal structures comprising actin filaments and their associated proteins in the postsynaptic actin cytoskeleton.

label.value: postsynapse of neuromuscular junction

value.value: The postsynapse of a neuromuscular junction. In vertebrate muscles this includes the motor end-plate, consisting of postjunctional folds of the sarcolemma.

label.value: excitatory chemical synaptic transmission

value.value: Synaptic transmission that results in an excitatory postsynaptic potential.

label.value: inhibitory chemical synaptic transmission

value.value: Synaptic transmission that results in an inhibitory postsynaptic potential.

label.value: glutamatergic synapse

value.value: A synapse that uses glutamate as a neurotransmitter.

label.value: polyadic synapse

value.value: A synapse consisting of a single presynapse and multiple postsynapses. These postsynapses may come from the same cell of from different cells. Polyadic synapses are common in arthropod and nematode central nervous systems.

label.value: presynaptic density

value.value: An electron dense specialization of the presynaptic active zone cytoskeleton.

label.value: cholinergic synapse

value.value: A synapse that uses acetylcholine as a neurotransmitter.

label.value: GABA-ergic synapse

value.value: A synapse that uses GABA as a neurotransmitter. These synapses are typically inhibitory.

label.value: symmetric, GABA-ergic, inhibitory synapse

value.value: A neuron to neuron synapse that lacks an electron dense postsynaptic specialization, uses GABA as a neurotransmitter and whose activity results in inhibitory postsynaptic potentials.

label.value: neuron to neuron synapse

value.value: A synapse in which pre and post-synaptic cells are neurons.

label.value: asymmetric, glutamatergic, excitatory synapse

value.value: A neuron to neuron synapse with a postsynaptic density, that uses glutamate as a neurotransmitter and whose activity results in excitatory postsynaptic potentials.

label.value: T-bar

value.value: A T-shaped presynpatic density. These are common in arhropod central nervous systems.

label.value: regulation of modification of synapse structure, modulating synaptic transmission

value.value: Any process that regulates the modification of synaptic structure and as a result regulates synaptic transmission.

definition.value: Note that this term was created for the SynGO project, and will be obsoleted when the SynGO annotations are made in Noctua.

label.value: G protein-coupled glutamate receptor activity

value.value: Combining with glutamate and transmitting a signal from one side of the membrane to the other by activating an associated G-protein, initiating a change in cell activity.

label.value: NMDA selective glutamate receptor signaling pathway

value.value: The series of molecular signals initiated by glutamate binding to an NMDA-selective glutamate receptor on the surface of the target cell, followed by the movement of ions through a channel in the receptor complex, and ending with the regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

label.value: AMPA selective glutamate receptor signaling pathway

value.value: The series of molecular signals initiated by glutamate binding to an AMPA-selective glutamate receptor on the surface of the target cell, followed by the movement of ions through a channel in the receptor complex, and ending with the regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

label.value: kainate selective glutamate receptor signaling pathway

value.value: The series of molecular signals initiated by glutamate binding to an kainate-selective glutamate receptor on the surface of the target cell, followed by the movement of ions through a channel in the receptor complex, ending with the regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

label.value: neuronal dense core vesicle

value.value: A dense core vesicle (granule) that is part of a neuron. These vesicles typically contain neuropeptides. They can be found in all parts of neurons, including the soma, dendrites, axonal swellings (varicosities) and synaptic terminals.

label.value: symbiont entry into host cell via disruption of host cell envelope

value.value: The disruption by a symbiont of host cell envelope components to allow entry into the host cell.

label.value: symbiont entry into host cell via disruption of host cell envelope lipopolysaccharide

value.value: The disruption by a symbiont of host cell wall lipopolysaccharides to allow entry into the host cell. For example a phage entering a Gram-negative bacterium may actively break down outer membrane lipopolysaccharides.

label.value: symbiont entry into host cell via disruption of host cell glycocalyx

value.value: The disruption by a symbiont of host cell capsule to allow entry into the host cell.

label.value: fusion of virus membrane with host outer membrane

value.value: Fusion of a viral membrane with the host cell outer membrane during viral entry.

label.value: extrinsic component of postsynaptic early endosome membrane

value.value: The component of the postsynaptic early endosome membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

label.value: extrinsic component of postsynaptic endosome membrane

value.value: The component of the postsynaptic endosome membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

label.value: symbiont genome ejection through host cell envelope, contractile tail mechanism

value.value: Entry of a symbiont's genome into the host cell through the host cell envelope via a contractile tail ejection system consisting of a baseplate, a central tube and an external contractile sheath. Upon binding to the host cell surface, the baseplate changes its conformation and triggers sheath contraction, driving the rigid internal tail tube through the cell envelope. Occurs in non-enveloped prokaryotic viruses.

label.value: symbiont genome ejection through host cell envelope, long flexible tail mechanism

value.value: Entry of a symbiont's genome into the host cell through the host cell envelope via a long, flexible tail ejection system consisting a baseplate, a central tube and a terminator complex which attaches the tail to the phage capsid. Upon binding to the host cell surface, the baseplate changes its conformation and triggers genome ejection into the host cell cytoplasm. Occurs in non-enveloped prokaryotic viruses.

label.value: symbiont genome ejection through host cell envelope, short tail mechanism

value.value: Entry of a symbiont's genome into the host cell through the host cell envelope via a short tail ejection system consisting a central tube, the connector which attaches the tail to the phage capsid and releases inner core proteins. Upon binding to the host cell surface, the phage displays a tube-like extension of its short tail that penetrates both host membranes. This tail extension comes from the release of viral core proteins with channel forming properties. Occurs in non-enveloped prokaryotic viruses.

label.value: vesicle-mediated transport in synapse

value.value: Any vesicle-mediated transport that occurs in a synapse.

label.value: extrinsic component of postsynaptic recycling endosome membrane

value.value: The component of the postsynaptic recycling endosome membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

label.value: symbiont entry into host cell via permeabilization of endosomal membrane

value.value: The entry of a symbiont into a host cell, following endocytosis, via permeabilization of the endosomal membrane by membrane penetration protein(s) of the symbiont. This process mediates the entry of some non-enveloped virus into eukaryotic cells. In some cases, viral membrane-penetration protein requires to be activated to display its membrane penetrating activity. Activation can be due to receptor binding or the acidic pH of the endosomal lumen.

label.value: extrinsic component of presynaptic endosome membrane

value.value: The component of the presynaptic endosome membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

label.value: symbiont entry into host cell via permeabilization of inner membrane

value.value: The entry of a symbiont into the cytoplasm of a host cell, following fusion with the outer membrane, via permeabilization of the plasma (inner) membrane. This process mediates the entry of some non-enveloped viruses into prokaryotic cells. In the case of some double stranded RNA viruses of prokaryotes this occurs via interaction of a membrane-interacting component of the capsid, leading to depolarization and permeabilization of the plasma membrane.

label.value: viral genome circularization

value.value: The circularization of a viral genome following infection of a host cell. This is common amongst bacterial viruses to protect the viral genome ends from nucleases, to convert the linear genome to an integrative precursor or to give rise to the replicative form of the genome. It can be mediated by covalent closure of the DNA sticky ends, recombinaison between redundant terminal sequences or via the binding of a protein at the viral DNA extremities.

label.value: modification of postsynaptic structure

value.value: Any process that modifies the structure of a postsynapse.

definition.value: This class does not cover assembly or disassembly of postsynapses, only the modification/remodelling of existing ones.

label.value: neuronal dense core vesicle exocytosis

value.value: The secretion of molecules (e.g. neuropeptides, insulin-related peptides or neuromodulators such as serotonin and dopamine) contained within a neuronal dense core vesicle by fusion of the granule with the plasma membrane of a neuron in response to increased cytosolic calcium levels.

label.value: neuronal dense core vesicle membrane

value.value: The lipid bilayer surrounding a neuronal dense core vesicle.

label.value: neuronal dense core vesicle lumen

value.value: The volume enclosed by a neuronal dense core vesicle membrane.

label.value: neuronal dense core vesicle organization

value.value: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of a neuronal dense core vesicle.

label.value: degradation of host chromosome by virus

value.value: The catabolic breakdown of the DNA of a host chromosome by a virus. This occurs during infection of bacteria by some phages. It frees up a large pool of nucleoside 5'-triphophates for use in viral DNA synthesis.

label.value: symbiont-mediated evasion of DNA end degradation by host

value.value: A process by which a symbiont evades and ends degradation of its DNA when free DNA ends are exposed. DNA ends are exposed during the life cycle of some viruses and these are targeted by host cells to destroy the virus. For example, some bacteriophages encode proteins that bind to free viral DNA ends, protecting them from degradation by host exonucleases.

label.value: maintenance of protein localization at cell tip

value.value: Any process in which localization of a protein is maintained at the cell tip.

label.value: symbiont-mediated evasion of host restriction-modification system

value.value: A process by which a symbiont evades the DNA restriction modification system of its host. This process occurs in phages to protein themselves from bacterial restriction enzyme systems. Some viruses encode their own methyltransferase in order to protect their genome from host restriction enzymes. Others directly inhibit restriction enzymes while some use unusual bases in their genome to avoid restriction.
